===Etymology===
{{etyl|ang}} {{term|bryht|lang=ang}}, metathesis of {{term|beorht|lang=ang}}, from {{proto|Germanic}} *''berhtaz'' (compare {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|brecht}}, {{etyl|no|-}} {{term|bjart}}), from pre-Celtic/Germanic *''bherh<sub>x</sub>gto'' (compare {{etyl|cy|-}} {{term|berth}} 'beautiful'), from {{proto|Indo-European}} *''bʰereg-'' 'to gleam, whiten' (compare {{etyl|mga|-}} {{term|brafad}} 'blink of an eye', {{etyl|sq|-}} {{term|bardhë}} 'white', {{etyl|ru|-}} ''brezg'' 'dawn, daybreak', {{etyl|lt|-}} {{term|brekšta}} 'to dawn', {{etyl|fa|-}} ''barâzîdan'' 'to shine', {{etyl|sa|-}} {{rfscript|Devanagari}} ''bhrájate'').

